      Private markets don=E2=80=99t like to go down
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about an enduring appeal of private investing =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0venture capital, private equity, non-traded real estate, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0which is that, when the stock market goes down, your private in=
vestments don=E2=80=99t have to. If you own public stocks, those stocks tra=
de every day, and if their prices go down then your portfolio is worth less=
. If you own private investments, they don=E2=80=99t trade every day, so yo=
u have a lot of flexibility in how you mark them to market. You can look at=
 discounted cash flow analyses and public comparables and appraisals and=C2=
=A0recent fundraising rounds and come to some estimate of the value, but th=
at estimate might be less volatile than a public stock price. And so=C2=A0i=
f you are a hedge fund that owns a bunch of public tech stocks and a bunch =
of private tech stocks, and the public stocks go down by 20%, you can say t=
hings like =E2=80=9Cour large private holdings to some extent insulated us =
from the downturn in public markets,=E2=80=9D and skeptical journalists and=
 investors can say things like =E2=80=9Cwell, did they really?=E2=80=9D
Obviously there are limits to this, and if there is a sustained downturn in=
 public markets because economic conditions have gotten worse and tech comp=
anies have a harder time raising money, you eventually have to mark down th=
e private stakes too. But you still have some room to argue about how much =
they are worth, and some incentives to make that number high.=C2=A0Here is =
a   Bloomberg News story about how hedge funds and mutual funds have been m=
arking their private tech stakes differently:

The pain =E2=80=94 and then the questions =E2=80=94 kept coming last year a=
s prominent hedge funds took turns marking down the value of their stakes i=
n private companies. Every time they wrote down holdings by millions, or ev=
en billions, of dollars, investors questioned whether they had gone far eno=
ugh. ...
Five mega-hedge fund firms =E2=80=94 Tiger Global Management, D1 Capital Pa=
rtners, Lone Pine Capital, Viking Global Investors and Coatue Management =
=E2=80=94 all ramped up their bets on startups in the past few years, wager=
ing that soaring valuations and a hot market for initial public offerings w=
ould reap massive rewards. ...
Dozens of the companies they bought into are also owned by mutual funds run=
 by the likes of Fidelity and T. Rowe Price that are required to disclose v=
aluations regularly. Mutual funds have been marking down some holdings even=
 more severely than the drop in public markets.
Mining data from thousands of mutual funds over the past year, Bloomberg tr=
acked down their valuations for 46 private companies that also count the fi=
ve hedge fund firms as investors. Of those, about 70% of the private compan=
ies had been marked down by mutual funds through September last year, with =
an average decline of 35%. Some holdings were slashed by as much as 85%. =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
In some cases, the data show hedge fund marks haven=E2=80=99t caught up.

Obviously you can raise your eyebrows at the hedge funds here, but there ar=
e some arguments that the hedge funds have it right:
Compared with mutual funds, hedge funds tend to be more sophisticated inves=
tors with greater influence at the startups they buy into. They may negotia=
te special terms for their stakes, such as representation on boards or pref=
erential treatment in future funding rounds or an anti-dilution clause. Mon=
ey managers who purchase large stakes or buy directly, instead of in the se=
condary market, may also get more frequent updates on the venture=E2=80=99s=
 performance. All of that can impact valuations.
Also:
Mutual funds offer an interesting comparison because they typically give cl=
ients more liquidity =E2=80=94 the ability to buy and sell anytime markets =
are open. That incentivizes mutual funds to update asset values quickly, ta=
king potentially more aggressive markdowns, so that clients who withdraw ar=
en=E2=80=99t overpaid. In contrast, hedge fund clients can typically pull c=
ash quarterly, and venture and private equity ones may be locked in for yea=
rs.
If you run a mutual fund, a high mark is good for investors who=C2=A0take m=
oney out, while a low mark is good for investors who=C2=A0keep money in.
  [4]
=C2=A0In conditions of uncertainty, you might be tempted to use a low mark =
to reward your loyal investors. If you run a hedge fund, the main temptatio=
n is to report better performance.
Also yesterday, in writing about these incentives,=C2=A0I said that venture=
 capitalists do not like down rounds because =E2=80=9Cthey have to tell the=
ir own investors that they lost money for them; their assets under manageme=
nt have gone down and they can=E2=80=99t charge as much in fees.=E2=80=9D T=
hat was a sloppy thing to say; in fact private investment funds normally ch=
arge management fees based on committed capital or investments at cost, and=
 performance fees based on realized returns, so fees on existing assets don=
=E2=80=99t directly motivate how they mark their assets. But the main point=
 is that reporting good performance to their investors is=C2=A0a motivator,=
 and marking down investments hurts with that. And marking up helps. A=C2=
=A02021 paper by Peter Pham, Nick Turner and Jason Zein finds =E2=80=9Cthat=
 venture capitalists (VCs) strategically enhance their current funds=E2=80=
=99 interim performance around new fundraising events=E2=80=9D: They =E2=80=
=9Ctend to invest in follow-on financing rounds of their existing portfolio=
 firms at abnormally high step-ups in valuation=E2=80=9D when they are in t=
he process of raising a new fund, because good interim performance impresse=
s investors and bad performance does not.=C2=A0
Elsewhere in  venture capital and public versus private markets:

Venture-capital firms that deployed a new strategy of holding stocks for lo=
nger have come to regret it amid last year=E2=80=99s market rout.=C2=A0
During the recent bull market, venture-capital investors that typically exi=
t a stock after taking it public held on to their shares in the hope of max=
imizing returns. Instead, the sharp selloff in technology stocks in 2022 ha=
s dealt a punishing blow to that strategy. Some of the splashiest startup s=
tocks from 2021 plunged, making it unlikely those investors will recover th=
e value of their earlier positions anytime soon, if at all.=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s the thing about public markets, sometimes=C2=A0they go down.

