   =20
 =20

What about the chief compliance officer of a crypto exchange? I feel like h=
istorically there the job was to set the dial somewhere in the middle;=C2=
=A0in the early days of Bitcoin, exchanges often had, you know, a 35%=C2=A0=
tolerance for crime, and that was often what customers wanted. But over tim=
e that tolerance has come down. Now, if you are a US-regulated public compa=
ny like Coinbase Global Inc., you are in almost the same sort of business a=
s a bank, and you ought to have the same zero-ish (ish!) tolerance for crim=
e that a bank would. But it takes time for attitudes and procedures to chan=
ge, and crypto exchanges grew quickly over the last few years, so a crypto =
exchange=E2=80=99s compliance department might be a little less sophisticat=
ed and experienced than a bank=E2=80=99s. Plus=C2=A0there is the demand sid=
e: Relatively few of a bank=E2=80=99s customers will be there to do crime, =
but the proportion might be higher at a crypto exchange.  Anyway:

Coinbase, a publicly traded cryptocurrency trading exchange based in the Un=
ited States, agreed to pay a $50 million fine after financial regulators fo=
und that it let customers open accounts without conducting sufficient backg=
round checks, in violation of anti-money-laundering laws.
The settlement with the New York State Department of Financial Services, an=
nounced Wednesday, will also require Coinbase to invest $50 million to bols=
ter its compliance program, which is supposed to prevent drug traffickers, =
sellers of child pornography and other potential lawbreakers from opening a=
ccounts with the exchange.

Here is the New York DFS  press release=C2=A0from yesterday, which says tha=
t Coinbase=E2=80=99s know-your-customer/customer due diligence program, =E2=
=80=9Cboth as written and as implemented, was immature and inadequate.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0And here is the=C2=A0consent order, which includes this anecdot=
e:
In the spring of 2021, an individual purporting to be an employee of a corp=
oration (=E2=80=9CCorporation A=E2=80=9D) was able to open an account on be=
half of Corporation A without authorization from that corporation, and with=
out the appropriate personal identification documentation required by Coinb=
ase policy. As part of a sophisticated fraud, the individual was able to su=
bmit an online request form to raise the daily withdrawal limit by 50 times=
, which was granted despite a total lack of account activity and, therefore=
, no evidence that the existing thresholds were insufficient for the custom=
er=E2=80=99s activity. Then, on a single day, the employee transferred more=
 than $150 million from Corporation A=E2=80=99s bank account (that the empl=
oyee had also gained unauthorized access to) into Corporation A=E2=80=99s C=
oinbase account. The employee then immediately converted the fiat funds int=
o virtual currency, then immediately moved the virtual currency to a wallet=
 off the Coinbase platform. Coinbase did not become aware of this activity =
until six days later, when Coinbase was contacted by Corporation A=E2=80=99=
s bank. Coinbase assisted with the investigation of law enforcement, which =
ultimately led to recovery of the funds.
To be fair he=C2=A0also=C2=A0tricked the company=E2=80=99s bank, so you can=
=E2=80=99t blame this one entirely on Coinbase.
  [5]
=C2=A0Also he presumably used Coinbase so that he could turn the money into=
 crypto and make off with it =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he just kept it in the US do=
llar banking system it could have been fairly easily recovered =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but in fact that didn=E2=80=99t work and the authorities got the money b=
ack. So this is not=C2=A0really=C2=A0an advertisement for the usefulness of=
 crypto for crime. Still the point is that not too long ago, =E2=80=9CI wil=
l steal $150 million from my employer, plop it into a newly opened Coinbase=
 account and immediately withdraw it to a wallet that I control=E2=80=9D wa=
s a more-or-less plausible way to use Coinbase for crime, and now presumabl=
y that loophole has closed.

