10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Good (alleged) scam</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simplest form of investment scam is that=
=C2=A0you promise people some attractive return on their investment, they l=
ike the promised return and give you their money,=C2=A0and=C2=A0you steal i=
t. In this scam, what sort of return should you offer your marks in order=
=C2=A0to maximize your take? There are two basic approaches, which are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A reasonable return, or</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">An insane return.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first approach was made famous by Bernie M=
adoff, who ran a gigantic Ponzi scheme that offered relatively modest, stab=
le, boring returns. The advantage of this approach is that it can attract s=
ophisticated investors: Madoff was able to raise money from rich people and=
 funds-of-funds because, in their obviously flawed due diligence, they conc=
luded that the returns he promised were plausible.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Rich people and funds-of-funds have lots of money, so Madoff was =
able to raise lots of money and keep the scheme going for a long time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second approach has some advantages too. F=
or one thing, people=C2=A0want high returns, so I guess the higher the retu=
rn you promise the more people will want it and the more money they=E2=80=
=99ll give you. Also, though, you are running a scam, so you mostly don=E2=
=80=99t <em>want</em> sophisticated investors. It is plausibly harder to tr=
ick sophisticated investors than it is to trick unsophisticated ones. This =
is like why <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/301643=
62.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS93aHktbmlnZXJpYW4tc2Nhb=
S1lbWFpbHMtYXJlLW9idmlvdXMtMjAxNC01/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4b51d5fe" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">advance-fee scam emails have lots of typos</a>: =E2=80=9CBy sending an =
initial email that's obvious in its shortcomings, the scammers are isolatin=
g the most gullible targets.=E2=80=9D Promising a 1,000,000% return ensures=
 that you never end up talking to anyone but the most gullible possible mar=
ks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also promising a 1,000,000% return is just ver=
y funny? Here=E2=80=99s a good <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbG=
Vhc2UvMjAyMy0y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2e99d0b0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Securities and E=
xchange Commission enforcement action</a> against an alleged vaguely crypto=
-ish=C2=A0fraud:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [yester=
day]=C2=A0charged Neil Chandran, Garry Davidson, Michael Glaspie, Amy Mosse=
l, Linda Knott, AEO Publishing Inc, Banner Co-Op, Inc, and BannersGo, LLC f=
or their involvement in a fraudulent investment scheme named CoinDeal that =
raised more than $45 million from sales of unregistered securities to tens =
of thousands of investors worldwide.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint filed=
 in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan, Chandran,=
 Davidson, Glaspie, Knott, and Mossel falsely claimed that investors could =
generate extravagant returns by investing in a blockchain technology called=
 CoinDeal that would be sold for trillions of dollars to a group of promine=
nt and wealthy buyers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trillions of dollars! An investing rule of thu=
mb like =E2=80=9Cif anyone pitching an investment ever uses the word =E2=80=
=98trillion,=E2=80=99 hang up=E2=80=9D would probably serve most people rea=
sonably well.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Anyway the entire <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsY=
WludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wLXByMjAyMy0yLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe3909059" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> SEC complaint</a> is a joy:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chandran, a recidivist securities =
law violator and convicted felon, claimed to own a unique blockchain techno=
logy that was on the verge of being sold for trillions of dollars to a grou=
p of reputable billionaire buyers (=E2=80=9CCoinDeal=E2=80=9D). Chandran fu=
rther claimed his business required interim=C2=A0 financial support until t=
he sale transaction closed. Together with and through other named Defendant=
s, Chandran targeted mostly unsophisticated investors with false and mislea=
ding promises and representations that investments in CoinDeal would soon y=
ield extremely high returns from the imminent sale of his business. Ultimat=
ely, there was no sale, and no distribution of proceeds, because CoinDeal w=
as a sham.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chandran typically provided status=
 updates on the supposed deal, including but not limited to: the involvemen=
t of foreign central banks and the United States Department of Homeland Sec=
urity; the latest board meetings of the consortium of wealthy buyers; the r=
ole of certain political figures; and the causes=C2=A0of =E2=80=9Ctemporary=
=E2=80=9D delays to the sale closing. These updates were designed to lull i=
nvestors and induce them to continue investing in CoinDeal.=C2=A0</p></bloc=
kquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CForeign central banks=E2=80=9D is an =
even more reliable red flag than =E2=80=9Ctrillions of dollars.=E2=80=9D An=
d:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the CoinDeal offering, Chan=
dran, Davidson, and Glaspie repeatedly represented that CoinDeal was on the=
 cusp of closing. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0For example, on March 21, 2019, Glaspie st=
ated in his online update that he expected CoinDeal to close later that day=
. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0On April 11, 2020, Glaspie stated in his online update tha=
t CoinDeal would be closing within three days. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0On January 11=
, 2021, Glaspie stated in his online update that CoinDeal would be closing =
by January 13, 2021.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then of course the =E2=80=9Cdeal=E2=80=9D woul=
d not close and there would be excuses, which included =E2=80=9Cthe enginee=
r =E2=80=A6=C2=A0called in sick yesterday=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe bank wa=
nts a new set of documents.=E2=80=9D And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on information from Chandran=
, Davidson falsely stated, during a teleconference on March 6, 2021, that B=
illionaire 1 and Billionaire 2 were each under consideration as the potenti=
al CEO for the CoinDeal business enterprise. Billionaire 1 is the founder a=
nd executive chairman of a large online retailing company. Billionaire 2 is=
 the CEO of an electric car company. During=C2=A0the same teleconference, D=
avidson falsely stated that CoinDeal had a market capitalization of $50 tri=
llion.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ooh, blind item!=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA large online =
retailing company,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9Can electric car company,=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0you get one guess about who those two billionaires are. And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glaspie offered increasingly extra=
vagant returns that grew from 10 times the investment amount in his updates=
 from early 2019 to 500,000 times the investment amount in updates from lat=
e 2021.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC prints different versions of the payou=
t table=C2=A0that Glaspie allegedly offered investors, which kept growing o=
ver time; by June 2021 it looked like this:</p>
<div class=3D"body-image" style=3D"margin: 20px 0px;">
<!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/it8jJflKWPfc/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/it8jJflKWPfc/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the highest tier, a $100,000 investme=
nt, that=E2=80=99s a 56 million percent promised return, not even counting =
the Bentley, which I guess <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2FyYW5kZHJpdmVyLmNvbS9iZW50bGV5L2=
NvbnRpbmVudGFsLWd0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB549fb1ea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> more than do=
ubles your money</a> right there. Also, I mean, imagine a world in which yo=
u put $25,000 into some investment and got back <em>ELEVEN POINT TWO FIVE B=
ILLION DOLLARS=C2=A0</em>and they also gave you a =E2=80=9C$35k car allowan=
ce!=E2=80=9D and you were=C2=A0<em>excited=C2=A0</em>for the car allowance?=
 Like, you check your bank balance, and it says $11,250,000,000, and then y=
ou go to the Subaru dealership and pick out a nice Forester in the <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc3ViYXJ1LmNvbS92ZWhpY2xlcy9mb3Jlc3Rlci9zcGVjcy10cmltLmh0bWw/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB1c60cee2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> top trim package</a> and the salesperso=
n is like =E2=80=9Cthat one is=C2=A0$36,495, let me tell you about our fina=
ncing options=E2=80=9D and you are like =E2=80=9Cactually I have a voucher?=
=E2=80=9D ELEVEN BILLION DOLLARS PLUS A CAR ALLOWANCE! Come on. This is so,=
 so stupid. Nobody could have fallen for this, except that people allegedly=
=C2=A0did, to the tune of $45 million, and those are the people you want wh=
en you=E2=80=99re running a scam. CoinDeal=E2=80=99s email list is worth a =
fortune.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My favorite part, though, might be the section=
 about Linda Knott. According to the SEC complaint, she didn=E2=80=99t know=
 these people, and wasn=E2=80=99t in any real sense=C2=A0a part of their al=
leged scam. She just used their alleged scam as a substrate to run her own =
alleged scam:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In February 2021, Knott learned of CoinDeal th=
rough one of Glaspie=E2=80=99s teleconferences and decided to invest $1,000=
. Knott did not know of Glaspie before listening to the teleconference, and=
 Knott did not conduct any independent research on Glaspie or CoinDeal befo=
re investing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After learning of the aforementioned payout sc=
ale and referral bonuses promised by Glaspie, Knott started collecting fund=
s for CoinDeal through an investor group called Together We Profit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Together We Profit was a loose arrangement of =
individuals interested in participating in CoinDeal.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 Knott f=
acilitated investment by lowering the barrier to entry for CoinDeal by allo=
wing prospective investors to participate for as little as $27, which was l=
ower than the amounts permitted by Glaspie. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During 2021, Knott raised at least $749,000 in=
 fiat currency and additional amounts in crypto currency from thousands of =
investors from multiple states, including Michigan, and multiple countries.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While Knott assured investors she would transm=
it all of their funds to CoinDeal, that was false. She enriched herself by =
misappropriating approximately $79,000 or more for personal use and purpose=
s unrelated to CoinDeal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, if you believe CoinDeal=E2=80=99s prom=
ises,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0then raising $749,000 from investors to put into CoinDeal would e=
arn those investors a return of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0my calculator says $421 bill=
ion? Plus like 10 Bentleys? They=E2=80=99ll hardly miss the $79,000 you tak=
e off the top.</p>
