adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Coinbase compliance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What about the chief compliance officer of a c=
rypto exchange? I feel like historically there the job was to set the dial =
somewhere in the middle;=C2=A0in the early days of Bitcoin, exchanges often=
 had, you know, a 35%=C2=A0tolerance for crime, and that was often what cus=
tomers wanted. But over time that tolerance has come down. Now, if you are =
a US-regulated public company like Coinbase Global Inc., you are in almost =
the same sort of business as a bank, and you ought to have the same zero-is=
h (ish!) tolerance for crime that a bank would. But it takes time for attit=
udes and procedures to change, and crypto exchanges grew quickly over the l=
ast few years, so a crypto exchange=E2=80=99s compliance department might b=
e a little less sophisticated and experienced than a bank=E2=80=99s. Plus=
=C2=A0there is the demand side: Relatively few of a bank=E2=80=99s customer=
s will be there to do crime, but the proportion might be higher at a crypto=
 exchange. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3016436=
2.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8wMS8wNC9idXNpbmVzcy9jb2luYm=
FzZS1zZXR0bGVtZW50LWFudGktbW9uZXktbGF1bmRlcmluZy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBc0c487a3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coinbase, a publicly traded cryptocurrency tra=
ding exchange based in the United States, agreed to pay a $50 million fine =
after financial regulators found that it let customers open accounts withou=
t conducting sufficient background checks, in violation of anti-money-laund=
ering laws.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The settlement with the New York State Departm=
ent of Financial Services, announced Wednesday, will also require Coinbase =
to invest $50 million to bolster its compliance program, which is supposed =
to prevent drug traffickers, sellers of child pornography and other potenti=
al lawbreakers from opening accounts with the exchange.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the New York DFS <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGZzLm5=
5Lmdvdi9yZXBvcnRzX2FuZF9wdWJsaWNhdGlvbnMvcHJlc3NfcmVsZWFzZXMvcHIyMDIzMDEwND=
E/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8f7d3f69" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> press release</a>=C2=A0from y=
esterday, which says that Coinbase=E2=80=99s know-your-customer/customer du=
e diligence program, =E2=80=9Cboth as written and as implemented, was immat=
ure and inadequate.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And here is the=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGZzLm=
55Lmdvdi9zeXN0ZW0vZmlsZXMvZG9jdW1lbnRzLzIwMjMvMDEvZWEyMDIzMDEwNF9jb2luYmFzZ=
S5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbbeee09f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">consent order</a>, which=
 includes this anecdote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the spring of 2021, an individu=
al purporting to be an employee of a corporation (=E2=80=9CCorporation A=E2=
=80=9D) was able to open an account on behalf of Corporation A without auth=
orization from that corporation, and without the appropriate personal ident=
ification documentation required by Coinbase policy. As part of a sophistic=
ated fraud, the individual was able to submit an online request form to rai=
se the daily withdrawal limit by 50 times, which was granted despite a tota=
l lack of account activity and, therefore, no evidence that the existing th=
resholds were insufficient for the customer=E2=80=99s activity. Then, on a =
single day, the employee transferred more than $150 million from Corporatio=
n A=E2=80=99s bank account (that the employee had also gained unauthorized =
access to) into Corporation A=E2=80=99s Coinbase account. The employee then=
 immediately converted the fiat funds into virtual currency, then immediate=
ly moved the virtual currency to a wallet off the Coinbase platform. Coinba=
se did not become aware of this activity until six days later, when Coinbas=
e was contacted by Corporation A=E2=80=99s bank. Coinbase assisted with the=
 investigation of law enforcement, which ultimately led to recovery of the =
funds.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair he=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>tricked =
the company=E2=80=99s bank, so you can=E2=80=99t blame this one entirely on=
 Coinbase.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also he presumably used Coinbase so that he could turn the money =
into crypto and make off with it =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he just kept it in the U=
S dollar banking system it could have been fairly easily recovered =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but in fact that didn=E2=80=99t work and the authorities got the m=
oney back. So this is not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>an advertisement for th=
e usefulness of crypto for crime. Still the point is that not too long ago,=
 =E2=80=9CI will steal $150 million from my employer, plop it into a newly =
opened Coinbase account and immediately withdraw it to a wallet that I cont=
rol=E2=80=9D was a more-or-less plausible way to use Coinbase for crime, an=
d now presumably that loophole has closed.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Celsius</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you lend your cryptocurrency to a=C2=A0cryp=
to shadow bank that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jItMDEtMjcvY2Vsc2l1cy1zLTE4LXlpZWxkcy1vbi1jcnlwdG8tYXJlLXRlbXB0aW5nLWFuZC1k=
cmF3aW5nLXNjcnV0aW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1=
haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW=
9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf83ed10" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  promises you an 1=
8% return</a>, and the crypto shadow bank goes bankrupt, do you automatical=
ly get your money back? I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDYveW91LWNhbi10LXRlbGwtYW5hbHlzdHMtdG9vLW11Y2g_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDEwNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB21920e37" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  asked that question last month</a>, and I felt th=
en =E2=80=94=C2=A0and still feel =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it answers itself. The=
 answer is no. When you loaned your crypto to the crypto shadow bank, you w=
ere taking credit risk; the crypto shadow bank was trying to use your crypt=
o to make more money (crypto) so it could pay you your return. When it fail=
ed to do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0when it lost your crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0it wen=
t bankrupt. If you storm in and say =E2=80=9Copen up the vault and give me =
my money back,=E2=80=9D the crypto shadow bank will say =E2=80=9Cno, you ha=
ve misunderstood how this works, we don=E2=80=99t have a vault, what we hav=
e is a bunch of investments that we use to make money to pay the 18% return=
 we promised you, and those went poorly.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of crypto shadow banks went bankrupt las=
t year, and people did storm in to demand that they open the vaults and giv=
e the money back, due to a series of misconceptions that we also talked abo=
ut last month. (The main ones: That the crypto was in=C2=A0a vault, or that=
 a crypto shadow bank is somehow a=C2=A0<em>bank=C2=A0</em>backed by regula=
tion or deposit insurance or whatever.) We talked about this because some c=
ustomers of Celsius Network LLC, a bankrupt crypto shadow bank, had filed a=
 motion in bankruptcy court arguing that they owned the crypto that they ha=
d deposited with Celsius as part of its =E2=80=9CEarn=E2=80=9D program, whe=
re Celsius took their crypto and invested it and paid high returns for a wh=
ile and then lost the crypto and went bankrupt.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius still has some crypto left, and those =
customers want a declaration that it belongs to them, somehow, rather than =
being part of the bankruptcy estate that can be used to pay them and any ot=
her Celsius creditors. This struck me as a crazy argument, and I guess I wa=
s right? Yesterday the judge in the bankruptcy case <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30164362.280519/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNlcy5zdHJld=
HRvLmNvbS9wdWJsaWMveDE5MS8xMTc0OS9QTEVBRElOR1MvMTE3NDkwMTA0MjM4MDAwMDAwMDA2=
Ny5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB57af6a73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ruled against the custo=
mers</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the cryptocurrency assets in the Earn Accou=
nts are owned by the Debtors, the Account Holders are unsecured creditors a=
nd their recovery depends on the distributions to unsecured creditors under=
 a confirmed chapter 11 plan, or under the Bankruptcy Code=E2=80=99s priori=
ty rules in the event of liquidation. A fundamental principle of the Bankru=
ptcy Code is equality of distribution. There simply will not be enough valu=
e available to repay all Account Holders in full. If only some Account Hold=
ers prevail with their arguments that they own the cryptocurrency assets in=
 their accounts, they hope to recover 100% of their claims, while most of t=
he Account Holders are left as unsecured creditors and may recover only a s=
mall percentage of their claims. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The crux of many objections to the Amended Mot=
ion is that Celsius=E2=80=99s ubiquitous use [in the terms of use that its =
customers agreed to]=C2=A0of the word =E2=80=9Cloan,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Clend=
ing,=E2=80=9D and other variations sits in direct conflict with the singula=
r clause transferring all title and rights of ownership to the Debtors. The=
se responses argue that this creates an ambiguity within the four corners o=
f the contract. But the use of the term =E2=80=9Cloan,=E2=80=9D or variatio=
ns of that term, do not contradict transfer of ownership of cryptocurrency =
assets to Celsius. The Account Holders argue that a layperson=E2=80=99s und=
erstanding of the term =E2=80=9Cloan=E2=80=9D means the Account Holder reta=
ins ownership of their Earn Assets but temporarily allows the use of the=C2=
=A0assets by the Debtors =E2=80=94but the Court cannot ignore the plain and=
 clear language in the Transfer of Title Clause.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Further, even if the Court found that Account =
Holders loaned digital assets to Celsius, Account Holders would still be un=
secured creditors. It is blackletter law that a loan of money or property t=
o another creates a debtor-creditor relationship. ... And absent a perfecte=
d security interest in tangible or intangible property, in the event of the=
 debtor=E2=80=99s bankruptcy, the creditor holds only an unsecured claim.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what to say except =E2=80=
=9Cyes, obviously, of course.=E2=80=9D If you lend money to a crypto firm t=
hat promises you an 18% return, and it goes bankrupt, you don=E2=80=99t get=
 your money back! That=E2=80=99s why it promised you an 18% return! What el=
se could possibly have been going on here?</p>
